Project Title

Business Problem

CARS24 faces the real-world problem of setting and recommending accurate, market-driven prices for used cars so that sellers can list their vehicles at competitive prices for faster sales without loss, while buyers can confidently identify fair-priced, high-value cars without the risk of overpaying.

Problem Statement

CARS24 needs a data-driven way to analyze used car listings across different cities to understand market demand, pricing patterns, and customer preferences in order to optimize car prices, increase faster sales, and maximize profit.

Project Objective

The main objective of this project is to collect real-time used car data from the CARS24 website and analyze it to understand market trends, pricing patterns, and customer demand so that better business decisions can be made.

In[1]:
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import numpy as np
import time
from selenium.webdriver import Edge
import pandas as pd

URL = 'https://www.cars24.com/buy-used-cars-'
CITIES = [
    'new-delhi', 'hyderabad', 'mumbai', 'bangalore',
    'chennai', 'jaipur', 'ahmedabad', 'kolkata',
    'noida', 'nagpur'
]

TARGET_RECORDS = 201       # minimum records to load before scraping
SCROLL_PAUSE = 3.5            # wait time after each scroll
MAX_SCROLLS = 30            # safety limit

car, varient, km, fuel, transmission, registration, price, location = [], [], [], [], [], [], [], []
driver = Edge()


for city in CITIES:

    driver.get(URL + city)
    time.sleep(5)

    last_count = 0
    scroll_count = 0

    while scroll_count < MAX_SCROLLS:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(driver.page_source)
        cards = soup.find_all('div', class_="styles_contentWrap__9oSrl")
        current_count = len(cards)


        if current_count == last_count or current_count >= TARGET_RECORDS:
            break

        last_count = current_count

        
        last_card = driver.find_elements(
            "css selector", "div.styles_contentWrap__9oSrl"
        )[-1]

        driver.execute_script(
            "arguments[0].scrollIntoView({block:'center'});",
            last_card
        )

        time.sleep(SCROLL_PAUSE)
        scroll_count += 1



    city_records = 0

    for c in cards:
        car.append(c.find('span', class_="sc-bcXHqh bAcffq").text if c.find('span', class_="sc-bcXHqh bAcffq") else np.nan)
        varient.append(c.find('span', class_="sc-bcXHqh bKVBht").text if c.find('span', class_="sc-bcXHqh bKVBht") else np.nan)

        info = c.find_all('p', class_="sc-bcXHqh kNDBvu")
        km.append(info[0].text if len(info) > 0 else np.nan)
        fuel.append(info[1].text if len(info) > 1 else np.nan)
        transmission.append(info[2].text if len(info) > 2 else np.nan)
        registration.append(info[3].text if len(info) > 3 else np.nan)

        price.append(c.find('p', class_="sc-bcXHqh hvRpEM").text if c.find('p', class_="sc-bcXHqh hvRpEM") else np.nan)
        location.append(city)

        city_records += 1
    print(f"Records scraped: {city_records}")



driver.quit()

df = pd.DataFrame({
    'car': car,
    'varient': varient,
    'km': km,
    'fuel': fuel,
    'transmission': transmission,
    'registration': registration,
    'price': price,
    'location': location
})

df.dropna(ignore_index=True).to_csv('Raw_Data2.csv', index=False)
print('total records scraped',len(df))
print(" Scraping completed successfully")

plt.show()

Insights:-

  • A few very expensive cars (outliers) exist; they can distort average price, so median price is better for recommendations.

  • The 28 lakh range dominates listings, making it the most important range for competitive pricing.

  • High price variation shows the need for segment-wise pricing (budget, mid, premium).

  • Skewed data means log transformation is useful for building accurate price prediction models.

#Are fuel preference and transmission related
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

table = pd.crosstab(df['fuel'], df['transmission'])
chi2, p, dof, ex = chi2_contingency(table)
print("p-value:", p)

p-value: 0.002689694897273817
In[100]:
sns.heatmap(table, annot=True, fmt='d')
plt.title("Fuel vs Transmission")
plt.show()

Insights:-

  • Fuel type and transmission are strongly related (p-value = 0.0026 < 0.05).

  • Petrol cars are mostly Manual mass market preference.

  • Diesel cars have higher Auto share premium and comfort-driven segment.

  • CNG is mostly Manual cost-saving buyers.

  • CARS24 must use fuel + transmission together for accurate price recommendations and demand matching.

In[101]:
#Does price differ significantly across fuel types
#Anova Test
from scipy.stats import f_oneway
groups = [g['price'] for _, g in df.groupby('fuel')]
f_oneway(*groups)
Out[101]:
F_onewayResult(statistic=np.float64(15.683561306862993), pvalue=np.float64(1.1793896781256903e-12))

Insights:-

  • Price differs significantly across fuel types (p-value 0.05).

  • Fuel type has a real and strong impact on resale value.

  • CARS24 cannot use a single pricing logic for all fuels.

  • Each fuel type needs a separate pricing adjustment factor.

  • Ignoring fuel type will cause overpricing or underpricing, reducing trust and faster sales.

  • KM and age together explain most of the price variation both must be used in pricing.

  • Price difference is linked with age (-0.39) older cars are more likely to be mispriced.

  • Actual price and expected price move almost perfectly together strong prediction alignment.

  • CARS24 pricing is mainly controlled by:

  • Expected price model Age KM, in that order of importance.
